# Production Security Baseline

- Treat every change as production code: prefer safe defaults, defensive checks, and explicit failure handling.
- Never hardcode secrets, tokens, API keys, private URLs, or credentials. Use secure config/env and keep secrets out of logs.
- Validate and sanitize all external/user input (client, API, Firestore payloads, query params, deep links).
- Enforce authorization at data boundaries: client checks are not enough; keep Firestore/backend rules aligned with access intent.
- Minimize data exposure: request/read/write only required fields, and avoid storing unnecessary sensitive data.
- Use structured error handling. Do not swallow errors silently; log actionable context without PII and return safe user-facing messages.
- Preserve backward compatibility for schema/contract changes. Prefer additive migrations and guarded rollouts.
- For auth/payment/notification flows, require idempotent writes and clear state transitions to avoid duplicate side effects.
- Keep dependencies current and trusted; avoid introducing unmaintained packages without strong justification.
- Add/maintain verification for critical paths (auth, payments, notifications, uploads): tests or reproducible manual checks are required before merge.

## Release Gate (must pass)

- No debug/test-only behavior in production paths.
- No placeholder/mock data in production screens unless explicitly feature-flagged.
- No sensitive data in analytics/crash logs.
- Build/lint/tests pass for touched surfaces.
